Yobe State governor, Mai Mala Buni, has refuted report suggesting that he suspended a village head for complaining of water scarcity, describing it as cheap blackmail and mischief. “The report is just an act of mischief and a cheap blackmail intended to mislead the public to give His Excellency the governor a bad name”, a statement by director-general of press and media affairs to the governor, Mamman Mohammed, noted. Mohammed said it was even curious that Governor Buni got to know of the purported suspension in the said report, adding that the governor wouldn’t have taken action on what he had no knowledge of. The DG continued: “For those who are conversant with the character of His Excellency Governor Mai Mala Buni, he always has listening ears to peoples’ problems and a very good heart of extending goodwill to solve such problems. “It becomes ironical for a person with this pedigree, to suddenly reprimand a community leader who is complaining for a public interest. The report is unkind to have reduced the personality of a governor to the suspension of a village head. “It is equally most unfortunate that Sahara Reporters lacked the courtesy and the basic etiquette of reaching out to the relevant quarters to balance and verify their report before going public which is putting the reputation of the media organization into question”. He implored the general public to disregard the said online report which he further described as baseless and fictitious in its entirety. Putting the records straight, Mohammed said, “His Excellency Governor Mai Mala Buni, has not heard of any suspension of a village head, has nothing to do with any purported suspension and will never encourage same for any one who will make case on behalf of his people. “It is also imperative to note that education, water, agriculture and power supply were among key sectors receiving government attention”. 